04524nam a22005895i 9780226563435DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265634357 a10.7208/97802265634352doi  a(DE-B1597)524889  a(OCoLC)1038717045  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH581.2 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a571.62231 aReynolds, Andrew S., eauthor.14aThe Third Lens :bMetaphor and the Creation of Modern Cell Biology /cAndrew S. Reynolds. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b17 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Early History of Cell Theory: The cell as empty chamber, building stone, and elementary organism -- t2. Biochemical Conceptions of the Cell: From bag of enzymes to chemical factory -- t3. Cell Sociology: The cell as social agent -- t4. Cell Signaling: The cell as electronic computer -- t5. Metaphors in Science: "Perspectives," "tools," and other meta- metaphors -- t6. The Instrumental Success of Scientific Metaphor: Putting the scientific realism issue into perspective -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDoes science aim at providing an account of the world that is literally true or objectively true? Understanding the difference requires paying close attention to metaphor and its role in science. In The Third Lens, Andrew S. Reynolds argues that metaphors, like microscopes and other instruments, are a vital tool in the construction of scientific knowledge and explanations of how the world works. More than just rhetorical devices for conveying difficult ideas, metaphors provide the conceptual means with which scientists interpret and intervene in the world. Reynolds here investigates the role of metaphors in the creation of scientific concepts, theories, and explanations, using cell theory as his primary case study. He explores the history of key metaphors that have informed the field and the experimental, philosophical, and social circumstances under which they have emerged, risen in popularity, and in some cases faded from view. How we think of cells-as chambers, organisms, or even machines-makes a difference to scientific practice. Consequently, an accurate picture of how scientific knowledge is made requires us to understand how the metaphors scientists use-and the social values that often surreptitiously accompany them-influence our understanding of the world, and, ultimately, of ourselves. The influence of metaphor isn't limited to how we think about cells or proteins: in some cases they can even lead to real material change in the very nature of the thing in question, as scientists use technology to alter the reality to fit the metaphor. Drawing out the implications of science's reliance upon metaphor, The Third Lens will be of interest to anyone working in the areas of history and philosophy of science, science studies, cell and molecular biology, science education and communication, and metaphor in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCells. 0aCytology. 0aMetaphor. 0aSciencexHistory. 4acell biology. 4acell theory. 4acell. 4aexplanation. 4ametaphor. 4ascientific realism. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226563435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226563435.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles